THE next chairman of the African Union Commission will have a long list of duties.This is according to the commission&rsquo;s outgoing chairwoman, Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma.She said most of the projects she initiated during her term were not things she could have completed in just four years.&ldquo;The work I have done needs continuous development as time progresses. In that way, we will be able to build a prosperous African continent.&rdquo; Dlamini-Zuma was delivering her state of the continent address at the Hilton Hotel in Durban, KZN, yesterday.She said among the plans in the pipeline was to modernise agriculture and to accommodate the youth. &ldquo;Today&rsquo;s young people can no longer be compared to the previous generation because of the everchanging technology.&ldquo;Agricultural equipment needs to be modernised. Our youth are different from the previous generation.&rdquo; She also spoke about the importance of education. &ldquo;The economy of today needs skills. We have initiated a skills revolution to have youngsters educated in various fields,&rdquo; she said.&ldquo;All countries should work towards ensuring that no child is denied access to education because of poverty.&rdquo; Dlamini-Zuma was accompanied by MECs Ravi Pillay, Weziwe Thusi and Bongi Sithole-Moloi, as well as other dignitaries.